{{Infobox book | image = | image_size = | border = | caption = | alt = Basic outlines of notable philosophers, and their philosophy in historical context | author = Paul Strathern | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = USA | language = | series = Philosophy in 90 Minutes; or Philosophers in 90 Minutes | subject = Philosophy and related history | genre = | publisher = [[Ivan R. Dee]] | publisher2 = [[Rowman & Littlefield]] | pub_date = | english_pub_date = | media_type = Book, Audio-book | pages = | awards = | isbn = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = }}
The '''''Philosophy in 90 Minutes series''''', written by [[Paul Strathern]], is a series of short introductory [[biographical]] overviews on well-known [[philosopher]]s, set in brief historical context, along with brief impressions of their philosophies. The books are also produced in [[audio format]]; read by narrator Robert Whitfield. The series’ intent is to "write about the philosophers' lives, [while] adding in a few of their ideas"<ref name=libjo> {{cite news | last = Goldsmith | first = Francisca | title = Series review | newspaper = Library Journal | publisher = Reed Business Information | date = November 1, 1996 | url =http://pohrebnibratrstvo.files.wordpress.com/2008/07/plato-in-90-minutes.pdf | accessdate =2013-07-06}} *Also, a web page with the [http://bookverdict.com/details.xqy?uri=Product-64411243129178.xml Library Journal review]</ref><ref name=daryl> {{cite news | last = Alexander | first = Daryl Royster |author2=Books section | title = Word for Word/90-Second Philosophy; In Bite-Size Portions, The Wise Men Made Easy | newspaper = New York Times | location = New York City | pages = | language = | publisher = The New York Times Company | date = May 14, 2000 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2000/05/14/weekinreview/word-for-word-90-second-philosophy-in-bite-size-portions-the-wise-men-made-easy.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm | accessdate =2013-07-06}}</ref><ref name=bern> {{cite news | last = Bernstein | first = Richard |author2=Arts section | title = Critic's Notebook; I Think, Therefore I Am, but There's So Little Time | newspaper = New York Times | location = New York City | pages = 02 | language = | publisher = The New York Times Company | date = July 2, 1998 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/02/books/critic-s-notebook-i-think-therefore-i-am-but-there-s-so-little-time.html | accessdate = 2013-07-06}}</ref>
==Contents== The books and audio presentations are considered to be outlines of the given philosopher. Interesting anecdotes about the subject are pervasive, and lines are quoted from published works in "an [[epigraph (literature)|epigraph]]ic style". Each volume contains relevant chronologies, including a [[history of philosophy|chronology of philosophy]] that is repeated in at least some books. Finally several suggested further reading titles are also included.<ref name=libjo/><ref name=bern/>
==Titles in the series== Some titles in series are: [[Socrates]], [[Plato]], [[Aristotle]], [[Confucius]], [[Machiavelli]], [[Descartes]], [[John Locke]], [[Hegel]], [[Heidegger]], [[David Hume|Hume]], [[Immanuel Kant|Kant]], [[Marx]], [[Rousseau]], [[Schopenhauer]], [[Spinoza]], and [[Nietzsche]].<ref name=daryl/><ref name=bern/>
